--- PDF SUMMARY (Document was 37 pages long) ---
The document was too long to read directly, so here is a detailed summary of all sections:

The paper "A Business by Any Other Name: Firm Name Choice as a Signal of Firm Quality" by Ryan C. McDevitt examines how the choice of a firm's name can signal its quality, using the plumbing industry as a case study. It finds that plumbing firms with names beginning with "A" or a number receive five times more service complaints and charge higher prices compared to other firms. These firms are also more prevalent in larger markets, which have consumers with higher search costs.

The study utilizes data from multiple sources, including the Better Business Bureau, Angie’s List, Yelp, and Dun & Bradstreet, to assess complaint ratios and ratings. It discovers that firms with alphanumeric names receive worse average ratings and more complaints per employee. Interestingly, firms that use both types of names (alphanumeric and others) recorded even worse service outcomes, garnering over 15 times as many complaints.

McDevitt reconciles these findings with a model considering firms of different qualities and consumers with varied search costs. Customers with low willingness to search might choose the first available listing, thus attracting less discerning clientele to alphanumeric firms. High-quality firms prefer clients with extensive projects, while low-quality firms lure uninformed, infrequent customers.

Moreover, the study found that firms advertising more in the Yellow Pages or on Google received more complaints, contradicting the expectation that advertising signals high quality. Firms using alphanumeric names also commanded an 8.4% price premium, particularly in metropolitan Chicago markets.

Overall, the paper concludes that lower-quality firms disproportionately choose prominent advertising methods and alphanumeric names to exploit consumer search behaviors. These practices increase asymmetrical information and affect consume
